description.text:
This is a loose recreation of one of Fortunado's Marionettes. This was inspired by a recent visit to the Guggenheim in NYC, where I saw firsthand some of the products of the Futurist movement nearly a century ago.   
What would Depero think of thingiverse? About the myriad tools and technologies that are now so accessible we can take them for granted?

I used default profiles in a Makerbot 5g, Makerbot filament, no rafts, on fixative-primed painters tape. My 5g is enclosed, and to prevent warping and curling in this print I warmed the enclosure to about 90F. I left a very slight gap at the arms allowing them to break free easily  to be removed and re-positioned on the body, welding with a soldering iron and bit of filament post-printing.

title: Lasercut tiles for Settlers of Catan

description.text: This item replaces the hexagonal tiles in Settlers of Catan with tiles that interlock.  It will produce the 19 hexagonal tiles that comprise the basic set, as well as a bunch of tokens to represent the ports.

The current latest version of this file is "catan9." The attached files are:
  • catan9.cdr -- for use with CorelDraw X5
  • catan9.x3.cdr -- for use with CorelDraw X3
  • catan9.svg -- for Inkscape and everybody else
    • This CDR file contains three layers:
  • a "cutting" layer containing nothing but vectors for cutting
  • a "raster" layer for etching
  • a "NOTES" layer for instructions (don't print)
    • Thing thing requires two passes on the laser cutter: an etching pass, which takes about 45 minutes on an Epilog Helix, and a cutting phase, which takes around 15 minutes on an Epilog Helix. Note that the "raster" layer contains some vectors. You need to either convert the entire raster layer to a bitmap (step 4 below), or else take other steps to ensure that the raster layer only etches, not cuts, your design. Suggested build process:

  • Materials: I've had good success using wood and cardboard for this design, and moderate success (so far) with etched acrylic.

  • Load up the design, and scale all layers to fit your material (but don't change the aspect ratio).

  • Test cut one of the surplus "port" tokens on the left side of the design to get your etch/cut settings right. After step 4, you won't be able to do individual token test-etches anymore.

  • In CorelDraw, select the entire "rasters" layer and convert it to a single bitmap (invoke "Bitmaps -> Convert to Bitmap..."). By consolidating all the bitmaps into one master bitmap, your laser cutter will etch more efficiently. Also, since the entire rasters layer is now a bitmap, you can fine-tune your laser parameters to have the bitmap settings for etching, and the vector art settings for cutting.

  • Delete the NOTES layer so that you don't accidentally cut it.

  • FIRE THE LAZZZOR! On TechShop's 65W Epilog Helix, this design took just under an hour to etch and cut into acrylic.
    • EXTRA CREDIT IDEAS:

  • Consider turning off the "rasters" layer altogether, and instead printing some very nice color printouts that you then glue onto your laser-cut pieces.

  • Consider cutting the different game pieces out of different colors of acrylic.

  • If you have suggestions for improved etchable artwork for the tiles, please submit them to me and I'll incorporate them into the design!

  • Consider flattring me: http://flattr.com/thing/134363/Lasercut-tiles-for-Settlers-of-Catan (Definitely not required, I'm just curious if this flattr thing will catch on.)

title: K8200 simple Z axis improvement - gain advantage of trapezoidal rod by deleting free play of the nut on the threaded rod

description.text:
Hi to all! It's my first thing uploaded there. I did it becauce I've face print quality issue. I found (as many of K8200 owners) that Z axis is weak. I doesn't move smootly and precise because of free play. Some people fix it by adding second leading rod or replacing threaded rod by trapezoidal rod. I found cheaper and faster solution. Nut and thread on the rod have some free play. Gravity force on the Z arm cancel it... but not enought when Z arm moving. I just add second M8 nut above stock nut holder with the spring beetwen them. Thingten additional nut to cancel free play and then assembled thing printed before. My holder dosent press on nut from top or bottom - it just prevent nut to spin You can see a picture of parts printed before (blue) and after (yellow) Gregor's advice ;)
Bulding manual for K8200 doesn't mention this but I strongly recomend to dissasemble linear bearing and aply grease inside bearing. Machinery oil is not enought to guarantee long life and smooth moving. I did it also on threader rod as you can see ;) Have fun!
Grzegorz "e_gregor"

Made on my K8200 regular printer. Parts needed:
1) spring, 20-30mm lenght, 8mm internal diameter
2) M8 nut
3) piece of filament ;)

Simple design easily printable.
intent is to print all three parts only needing 3 608 bearings the bold and a tap of your choosing.

The idea is to partially tap the small cylinder with the tap you intend to use. then push same said cylinder into the bearing which will allow you to bring the side of the tap into contact with the bolt which is supported by two bearings and captured by a bolt and what ever length spacers needed to hit the location that you wish to hob. then apply smooth pressure and perhaps assist bolt in rotation if movement doesn't come by its self. then continue to spin drill and apply pressure gently until you have the desired depth of cut.
repeat for quickly and accurately hobbing multiple bolts. I have not yet printed or tested this one, as I use a lathe to do this, but I wanted to offer another option to the guy with only a drill at home. if you choose to print this before I do please provide feedback.

A ghetto wireframe view for OpenSCAD using GLIntercept.

Now while moving the 3d view, hit the keyboard shortcut ctrl-shift-w to enable wireframe. Due to a bug, the keyboard shortcut only seems to work while manipulating the 3d view.

This thing is a lightweight, open, rear-loading clip-in frame for the GoPro Hero 3. The camera can be removed from and returned to the frame without moving the mount or removing the frame. But with access to all the buttons, mics, connectors, SD card and battery you can completely service the Hero 3 while in the frame. The bottom, being closed, does not provide access to the battery on the Hero 4, but the open back should allow usage of the display screen. (I don't have a Hero 4, so I can't say for sure.) Slots on the retainer clips allow for an optional Velcro strap or zip tie to fully secure the camera. A faceplate covers the face of the camera to prevent the shiny silver surface from reflecting into the image off a window. I cannibalized some parts of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:507061 for this, but the rest I created in Lightwave Modeler and exported to STL.

I printed this just fine with 100% Fill Density and otherwise mostly "normal print quality" settings on a new Ultimaker 2. Print time was just under two hours. The overhang bridges on the slots were a bit ragged and could maybe use some supports. But as the result was totally functional and better than expected I let it be. I sanded the front of the faceplate to remove the gloss of the plastic and present a more matte finish to reduce glare when used behind glass.

title: Improved Z-probe limit switch holder for Auto Bed Leveling

description.text:
This is a remix of the Z-probe holder designed by Michael Zenner (zennmaster), thing #167430.
Since not all extruders are created equal, the lever length is adjustable / customizable. Also one can use either M2.5 screws and nuts (hard to find, for me at least) or a small nylon tie to hold the limit switch.
I improved a few other small details (better fit of the servo arm, reinforcement, etc) while sticking to the original design.
OpenSCAD source is included so this part can be further remixed.
Thanks to Michael for his original design and the clear, easy to follow explanations on his blog and YouTube videos!

Printed here in PLA with 35% infill. The nylon tie must be tight around the limit switch so it does not move at all!  
Note that the total distance between the center of the servo shaft and the tip of the limit switch will be approximately the arm length + 8mm i.e. for an arm length of 37mm (default value) the total distance is 45mm.

Two different hitch cover designs; one with a horse symbol and one with a geometric shape.  These are designed to be attractive covers for hitch receivers.  There is a hole so that you can bolt it into the hitch receiver so that it doesn't bounce out or sprout wings.  
The final version is slightly redesigned to shorten it and speed up print times.  However, I now wonder if my hitch sleeve has a hole where others don't - if I need to bring back the previous version that has the hole further out, let me know.  My setup may be nonstandard.

Designed for no supports. I used flexible filament - this is the perfect material for this kind of application. Flexible TPU Polyurethane Filament - GREY http://filaments.ca/collections/flexible-filaments/products/flexible-tpu-polyurethane-filament-grey-1kg-spool Temp - 220 C
Extruder speed - 30 mm/s
Infill - 25%

title: Landing Gear for Blackout Mini Spider Hex (rev.2)

description.text:
I wanted something more elegant than attaching bars or helicopter skids to the Spider Hex. Most of the parts are press-fitted, with 4 inch zip ties for extra security. Everything in photos printed with opaque black PLA, tested on Printrbot. Modeled in 3ds Max.  
Previous iteration of the landing gear didn't have the crossbeam (part02). Structurally, it was strong enough and popped off in a crash as expected, but the lack of a perpendicular plate on the other side meant it wiggled just a little bit. I didn't want it to generate vibrations so I added the plate in version 2.

Press part02 into slots in part01, flat side. Secure with a pair of 4" zip ties through the holes.  
One zip tie keeps part02 from separating from part01 in a crash and over time. The second zip tie keeps the clamp fit from separating in a crash too easily.  
Clamp near the base of the front and rear arms of the Spider hex, should fit with a snap. Keep them from sliding towards the edge of the arm with zip ties attached to the arms (I use these zip ties for attaching the ESCs)

title: Layer fan duct and mount for Direct Drive Extruder

description.text:
This is a layer fan duct and mount kit for Marty Rice's awesome Direct Drive Extruder, when used with an E3D hotend. Together with the E3D 40mm cooler fan duct and mount kit I published earlier (thing #569877), it provides a complete cooling solution for Marty's extruder when used with an E3D-type hotend.  
Because of space constraints, a commonly available 5015S 12V blower (centrifugal) fan is used, a mount piece is provided that attaches the fan to the extruder body. The mount piece uses 1 x M4 25mm bolt, washer and nut to attach to the fan, and 1 x M3 20mm bolt, washer and nut to attach to the extruder body.  
The OpenSCAD source code for the layer fan duct is based on an earlier design by darco (Robert Quattlebaum), I cleaned up the code a little bit and modified it for this particular application.  
The OpenSCAD sources for both the fan duct and mount piece are included so both parts can be further remixed.
Printed both parts in PLA with 35% infill. And as seen on one of the pictures, the fan duct can be printed without support.

title: Printrbot Simple 1405 Maker Raspberry Pi Camera Mount

description.text: This camera mount attaches to the Printrbot Simple 1405 and uses the camera board case, and hinge, from DanielBull's project for the Mendel90. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:239268 This mount assumes that the Raspberry Pi is mounted on the left side rear of the PrintrBot Simple. I am using it along with OctoPrint to monitor and control my printer.

This should print fine without support. In fact support will most likely clog the hole for the camera hinge post. Print one of this part, plus the
camera_mount_front.stl
camera_mount_back.stl
camera_mount_hinge.stl
from DANIELBULL's project at:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:239268/ I have noticed that slicer has added some odd rounding on one edge of the bracket, but I have been unable to locate the cause in the STL. Aside from aesthetics it has not compromised the print nor its functionality.
